<section id="fs-idp25496592" class="free-response">
<title>Free Response</title>
<exercise id="fs-idm158896128">
<problem id="fs-idm142956128"><para id="fs-idm244442352">Why are the loop of Henle and vasa recta important for the formation of concentrated urine?</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-idp14658704"><label/>
<para id="fs-idm155407552">The loop of Henle is part of the renal tubule that loops into the renal medulla. In the loop of Henle, the filtrate exchanges solutes and water with the renal medulla and the vasa recta (the peritubular capillary network). The vasa recta acts as the countercurrent exchanger. The kidneys maintain the osmolality of the rest of the body at a constant 300 mOsm by concentrating the filtrate as it passes through the loop of Henle.</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-idm70793696">
<problem id="fs-idm182599536"><para id="fs-idm88522912">Describe the structure of the kidney.</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-idm157039072"><label/>
<para id="fs-idm116210384">Externally, the kidneys are surrounded by three layers. The outermost layer is a tough connective tissue layer called the renal fascia. The second layer is called the perirenal fat capsule, which helps anchor the kidneys in place. The third and innermost layer is the renal capsule. Internally, the kidney has three regions—an outer cortex, a medulla in the middle, and the renal pelvis in the region called the hilum of the kidney, which is the concave part of the “bean” shape.</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
